It is reported that the hydroxyl groups possess strong affinity towards Fe3+ and this characteristic has been utilized to prepare multi-hydroxyl magnetic gels and nanoparticles [35–37]. Hence, in this case, the SQDs with numerous surface hydroxyl groups may show sensitive fluorescence towards Fe3+. As expected, with the gradual addition of Fe3+, the fluorescence intensity of SQDs decreased continuously (Fig. 2c). With 300 μM of Fe3+, the I/I0 value (I and I0 are the fluorescence intensity of SQDs dispersion in the presence and absence of Fe3+, respectively) reaches as high as 91%. It is worth noting that the I/I0 value exhibits a good linear relationship versus the Fe3+ concentration in the range of 0.05–120 μM (R
                        2 = 0.9945) (Fig. 2d). The limit of detection (LOD) of SQDs for Fe3+ was measured to be 102 nM at the signal-to-noise ratio of 3. Such a high sensitivity is comparable to that of many reported fluorescent probes [38–40] ( Table 1
                        ), and is sensitive enough to meet the standard of Fe3+ concentration in drinking water in China (0.30 mg/L, about 5.36 μM). Additionally, the fluorescence quenching process is very fast and can be accomplished within 1 min (Fig. S5).
